<subsection xml:id="subsec-vectors-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Vectors in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_cttmh963">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_vqbsodw1">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cjjfcf40">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7wp0nbe2">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_n8kt91zm">
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_sd13915o">
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bn4dn3pp">
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_3gduhrup">Explain the terms distance, displacement, speed, velocity and acceleration in real-life situations; determine velocity and acceleration in different situations</p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
            <li xml:id="auto_dh8zr30w" component="lesson-plan">Grade Level: 10</li>
            <li xml:id="auto_odnxqpxa" component="lesson-plan">Estimated Duration: 40 minutes</li>
            <p xml:id="auto_zht206q8" component="lesson-plan">
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="auto_l0kvtnxf">
                        <title>Know</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_sxskbriu">Scalar quantities (distance, speed) have magnitude only; vector quantities (displacement, velocity, acceleration) have both magnitude and direction.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0kb4jaw6">
                        <title>Do</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_y11lafd4">Distinguish between scalar and vector quantities, and calculate speed, velocity, and acceleration from given data.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4gfafqzz">
                        <title>Apply</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_3i4e3aui">Use vector concepts to analyse real-world motion in transport, sports, navigation, and engineering.</p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_q0bg7vio">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/vectors-in-real-life.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ex42cd1v">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_vectors-in-real-life.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_no7b1iih">
            <alert>Anchor Activity — Analysing Motion with Scalar and Vector Quantities</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nq9xnfm8">
            <em>Objective:</em> Students discover the distinction between scalar and vector quantities
            through hands-on calculation. They find that distance and speed (scalars) differ from
            displacement and velocity (vectors) because vectors include direction.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_b11o5crw">
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_klevowy6">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_cffjkvwd">Organise students into groups of 2–3; distribute rulers, graph paper, and calculators.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2regc8s2">Guide students to draw a horizontal line representing east–west motion.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a1ck8bdg">Help students mark the starting point, 4 km east, then 3 km back west.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bqc9wj1a">Encourage students to calculate distance (<m>4 + 3 = 7</m> km) and displacement (<m>4 - 3 = 1</m> km east).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9ltbg08r">Ask probing questions: <q>Is the total path the same as the final position?</q> <q>Does direction matter for speed?</q></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zt62hekb">Guide calculation of speed <m>= 7 \div 2 = 3.5</m> km/h and velocity <m>= 1 \div 2 = 0.5</m> km/h east.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_o0je88je">Use student discoveries to introduce scalar vs.\ vector terminology.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bc8th34h">
            <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ei6ws1lg">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_9t0olwvq">Which quantities depend only on size?</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a7oeuahk">Which quantities depend on both size and direction?</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_91wjgxnf">Why are speed and velocity different even though they both measure “how fast”?</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <introduction xml:id="auto_hiaoj9r1">
        <p xml:id="auto_zc7lbxnx">
            In daily life, we describe motion using quantities such as distance, speed and direction.
            Some quantities depend only on size, while others depend on both size and direction.
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_wxohxsuc">
            A <term>scalar quantity</term> has magnitude only.
            Examples include distance, time and speed.
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_l6vdnuej">
            A <term>vector quantity</term> has both magnitude and direction.
            Examples include displacement, velocity and acceleration.
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_cjgcakd3">
            Vectors help us describe motion accurately in transport, sports, navigation and engineering.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <activity xml:id="auto_2d8tg65i">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_izq6pwci">
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jskwb6y8">
                <term>Materials:</term> Ruler, graph paper
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ufu7rr17">
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_bil0nbid">
                A student walks <m>4 \, \text{km}</m> east and then 
                <m>3 \, \text{km}</m> west.
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_peobqtlq">Draw the movement on a straight line.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3svmygk9">Find the total distance travelled.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_v557k066">Determine how far the student is from the starting point.</li>
            </ol>
            <p xml:id="auto_vmup0jcg">
                Now suppose the total time taken is <m>2 \, \text{hours}</m>.
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_188dvd2i">Calculate the average speed.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_csrbzv51">Calculate the average velocity.</li>
            </ol>
            <p xml:id="auto_lwsdq8kd">
                In your group discuss:
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_o2wfgb9c">Which quantities depend only on size?</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0butvx7g">Which quantities depend on both size and direction?</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight xml:id="auto_3lwu02ps">
        <p xml:id="auto_dkh51ahh">
            <term>Distance</term> is the total path travelled. It is a <term>scalar</term> quantity(has only magnitude).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ybium0mx">
            <term>Displacement</term> is the straight-line change in position together with direction. It is a <term>vector</term> quantity (has both magnitude and direction).
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_wf6zogh2">
            <term>Speed</term> is the rate of change of distance.
            <me>
                \text{Speed} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Time}}
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0s73w6zz">
            Speed is a scalar quantity.
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_1qsfqlgx">
            <term>Velocity</term> is the rate of change of displacement.
            <me>
                \text{Velocity} = \frac{\text{Displacement}}{\text{Time}}
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_99rx5gst">
            Velocity is a vector quantity.
        </p>

        <p xml:id="auto_u0cizkiy">
            <term>Acceleration</term> is the rate of change of velocity.
            <me>
                \text{Acceleration} = \frac{\text{Change in velocity}}{\text{Time}}
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_a475gq6o">
            Acceleration is also a vector quantity.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_sa5efv0f">
            After students share their findings, formalise their discoveries with these key concepts.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_j1rxqqrn">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies — Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_e2gmq7t1">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_8ncfkehw">Clarify that speed uses total distance, while velocity uses displacement.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mgbjo5zo">Emphasise that vectors <em>always</em> include direction.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5akxkwl5">Show that velocity can be zero even when speed is not (circular motion).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w6slheol">Use consistent units (km/h or m/s) throughout calculations.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ttrnux5t">Connect formulas to real-world contexts (car speedometers show speed, not velocity).</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (15 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_r353d5ii">
            Work through the textbook examples on the board, inviting students to supply each step.
            Highlight the distinction between magnitude-only answers (speed, distance) and
            magnitude-plus-direction answers (velocity, displacement). After the worked examples,
            assign the practice exercises for independent work.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_no0m5o7a">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_cjtcjr82">
                A cyclist rides <m>30 \, \text{km}</m> east in <m>2 \, \text{hours}</m>. Find:
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_50w5hhro">the speed,</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_s7gcrvl6">the velocity.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_8fr57ld6">
                Speed = <m> \frac {\text{Distance}}{\text{Time}} = \frac{30}{2} = 15 \, \text{km/h}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_iw9x8ur4">
                Velocity = <m> \frac {\text{Displacement}}{\text{Time}} = \frac{30}{2} = 15 \, \text{km/h east}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_0odyjxh5">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_v3i7coxo">
                A vehicle increases its velocity from <m>8 \, \text{m/s}</m> to <m>20 \, \text{m/s}</m> in <m>4 \, \text{s}</m>. Find its acceleration.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_pyn0x5ch">
                Change in velocity = <m>20 - 8 = 12 \, \text{m/s}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_cw9u8xlg">
                Acceleration = <m>\frac{12}{4} = 3 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_ofko53tg">
            <alert>Exit Ticket</alert> — Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_srom6d8p">
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> A truck moves 50 km north in 1 hour, then returns 20 km south in 0.5 hours.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8468a1ot">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_7egeyf6a">Find the total distance travelled.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_x9goix3v">Find the displacement.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ero12xsh">Calculate the average velocity for the entire journey.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3gpnhila">
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> A car changes its velocity from <m>15\text{ m/s east}</m> to <m>5\text{ m/s east}</m> in <m>2\text{ s}</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8nu9uwc2">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_jcpa39dm">Find the change in velocity.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ms4700dx">Calculate the acceleration.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lyjgjyff">Explain whether the car is speeding up or slowing down.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_a5p5g9hj">
            <alert>Question 3:</alert> Explain the difference between speed and velocity using a real-life example.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o7nu9ggt">
            <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_44fsim1b">
            <alert>Q 1:</alert> (a) Distance <m>= 50 + 20 = 70</m> km. (b) Displacement <m>= 50 - 20 = 30</m> km north.
            (c) Total time <m>= 1.5</m> h; average velocity <m>= 30 \div 1.5 = 20</m> km/h north.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o4k5j5zv">
            <alert>Q 2:</alert> (a) Change in velocity <m>= 5 - 15 = -10</m> m/s.
            (b) Acceleration <m>= -10 \div 2 = -5\text{ m/s}^2</m>.
            (c) The car is slowing down (decelerating) because the acceleration is negative.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ky0csc7q">
            <alert>Q 3:</alert> Speed is how fast you travel regardless of direction; velocity includes direction.
            For example, driving at 60 km/h in a circle: speed is constant at 60 km/h, but velocity
            changes continuously because direction changes.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="auto_6m57lzlq">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_jfvlbh3d">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_fhmf9o62">
                    A learner walks <m>5 \, \text{km}</m> north and then <m>3 \, \text{km}</m> south.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1m8miio6">
                    Find:
                        <ol marker="i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_xlpghgor"> the total distance,</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_bkfucwss"> the displacement.</li>
                        </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_6lgetuk8">
                    Distance = <m>8 \, \text{km}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_hxtu0h4x">
                    Displacement = <m>2 \, \text{km north}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_ipra1wen">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_hqiz50cc">
                    A car travels <m>180 \, \text{km}</m> in <m>3 \, \text{hours}</m>. Find its speed.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_riclk74x">
                    <m>60 \, \text{km/h}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_mc38slwb">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_mdwvgvbt">
                    A boat moves <m>40 \, \text{km}</m> west in <m>2 \, \text{hours}</m>. Find its velocity.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_v5pwnvmn">
                    <m>20 \, \text{km/h west}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_ff9dl9o4">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_apynzcu0">
                    A bus moves from rest to <m>25 \, \text{m/s}</m> in <m>5 \, \text{s}</m>. Find its acceleration.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_3jla5tbb">
                    <m>5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_8ceo4jj8">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_c2t1v399">
                    A runner completes one full lap of <m>400 \, \text{m}</m> in <m>50 \, \text{s}</m>.
                    Find:
                        <ol marker="i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_w3wcis1h">the distance travelled,</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ho8nfyjt">the displacement.</li>
                        </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_u8g3c6gk">
                    Distance = <m>400 \, \text{m}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ex2durfo">
                    Displacement = <m>0 \, \text{m}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_2s392p1h">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qlk851gy">
                    A car changes its velocity from <m>15 \, \text{m/s east}</m> to <m>5 \, \text{m/s east}</m> in <m>2 \, \text{s}</m>. Find its acceleration.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_xkl7d6uw">
                    <m>-5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_762e5ip7">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_0uqbmp1q">
                    A cyclist travels <m>12 \, \text{km}</m> north and then <m>9 \, \text{km}</m> east. Determine the total distance travelled.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_yrzjvzra">
                    <m>21 \, \text{km}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_b0wtpt93">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_hpamn6cr">
                    A delivery rider travels <m>6 \, \text{km}</m> east and then <m>8 \, \text{km}</m> east in a total time of <m>2 \, \text{hours}</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_evk3igbg">
                    Find:
                        <ol marker="i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_bnbq6hus">the total distance travelled,</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_4bgd5qft">the velocity of the rider.</li>
                        </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_s9e2im2v">
                    Distance = <m>14 \, \text{km}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xzjq7c2p">
                    Velocity = <m>7 \, \text{km/h east}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_muho45aa">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_u8vbbh3k">
                    A truck moves <m>50 \, \text{km}</m> north in <m>1 \, \text{hour}</m>, then returns <m>20 \, \text{km}</m> south in <m>0.5 \, \text{hours}</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_54m21cwm">
                    Find:
                        <ol marker="i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_q7zpz6xp">the total distance travelled,</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_z0h4ta1x">the displacement,</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ad64taib">the average velocity for the entire journey.</li>
                        </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_x4scyxsl">
                    Distance = <m>70 \, \text{km}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_6wqfrqk0">
                    Displacement = <m>30 \, \text{km north}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xferemp2">
                    Average velocity = <m>20 \, \text{km/h north}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_q819jkxj">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_kzdwl8vp">
                    A car accelerates from rest to <m>30 \, \text{m/s}</m> in <m>6 \, \text{s}</m>. Find its acceleration.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_hnmjygfa">
                    <m>5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_2dqzhg4u">
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qqexctqt">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_njffk4il">Provide formula reference cards for speed, velocity, and acceleration.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_154cbnra">Use colour coding: blue for scalars (distance, speed), red for vectors (displacement, velocity).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ag4pkjzn">Start with one-dimensional motion (east–west only) before introducing multiple directions.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_h8vfgl32">Allow calculators for all calculations.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_sb9citgh">Provide step-by-step worked-example templates.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ce9qsqg7">Use visual diagrams extensively.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_w8gsbp5y">
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vzih2jb7">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_q4jskl4v">Introduce two-dimensional velocity problems (north and east components).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9zosh5no">Explore relative velocity (two objects moving).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xdqnaofn">Challenge with non-uniform acceleration problems.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_f4lcya96">Connect to vector addition and the Pythagorean theorem.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hekmyyel">Analyse real sports data (100 m sprint acceleration profiles).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5fhs3670">Introduce instantaneous vs.\ average velocity.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_x25ty3bi">
            <alert>Extension Activity — Real-World Motion Analysis Project:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_35dcfe7b">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_k0kpl1mc">Choose a real-world scenario: commute to school, sports activity, delivery route, or public transport.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_66f7tn4l">Record or estimate: total distance, displacement, time taken.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_leq74ra8">Calculate: average speed and average velocity.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gm6xu8bf">Draw a diagram showing the path and displacement vector.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a12q5qbz">Explain why speed and velocity differ in your scenario.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5mlur0mw">Present findings to the class with visual aids.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
</subsection>